New dialogue with Ovagos (string_id: "lord_1_73", 8 messages):
  Player: greetings my lord, do you carry any news
  Ovagos: *I pull my horse to a halt, the lamellar of my armor clinking softly in the cool night air. I look down at the traveler and his small band, my expression unreadable under the moonlight.* 

Greetings. You find us in a rare moment of quiet; the borders are still and the swords of the Empire remain sheathed for now. Peace is a heavy thing to carry, is it not? Beyond that, the roads near Veron remain safe under my watch. What brings a man of your... modest company into these lands at such an hour?
  Player: How would a humble soldier as myself gain renown 
  Ovagos: *I adjust my reins, the rings of my mail whispering against my surcoat. I look toward the dark tree line where my scouts have reported movement.* Renown is a heavy coin, friend. It is not found in the bottom of a flagon, but in the balance of a blade. For one with a... modest following, look to the shadows. Clear the roads of the forest filth and looters that plague our borders. Each bandit head is a tally on the ledger of your name. Prove you can protect the flow of trade, and the world will begin to weigh your worth differently. There are tracks not far from here; perhaps your destiny begins there?
  Player: i am more skileld than my outlook might suggest. who is the strongest and meanest bandit in these lands
  Ovagos: *I lean forward slightly, the heavy scales of my armor shifting with a rhythmic metallic groan.* A bold claim, stranger. The balance between confidence and folly is often thinner than a worn denarius. If you seek a true weight to test your mettle, there is a band of forest filth lurking not seven miles from here. They are led by one who knows these woods better than his own palms. By the Great Scales, if you truly possess the skill you claim, their heads would be a fine down payment on your reputation. Shall we see if your blade is as sharp as your tongue?
  Player: take me to this bandit camp and i will show my worth
  Ovagos: *I let out a short, dry chuckle that barely rattles my gorget.* You wish for a guide? A lord does not usually play scout for a band of seven. However, I have a ledger to balance, and those bandits are a debt long overdue. Follow my banner. I will lead you to the edge of their shadow, but do not expect my legionaries to draw steel for your glory. This is your gamble, stranger. If you break them, the roads are cleaner and your name gains weight. If you fall... well, the crows must eat too. Shall we?
