  Player: greeting my king. I want to prove my worth to you and gain your alligiance. Let me fight your best man in a dual and i will take his place as your bodyguard
  Derthert: *I pull the reins of my horse, narrowing my eyes at the bold stranger. My knights shift in their saddles, hands resting near their sword hilts.* You speak with the confidence of a man who has never seen a Vlandian lance charge, traveler. My bodyguards have earned their place through years of service and blood, not a single bout of sport. If you seek to prove your worth to the crown, do so through deeds, not by brawling with my kin on the roadside. Tell me, who are you to demand such a prize?
  Player: I am the hedgeknight of these parts. I wish not to cause trouble but to prove my worth. Show you people that you value skill and meritocracy over nepotism
  Derthert: *I let out a short, dry chuckle, the sound muffled by my gorget.* Meritocracy? You speak like an Imperial scholar, yet you dress for the mud. God's grace be upon us, for even the birds of the air know that a kingdom is held together by more than just a sharp edge. If you truly wish to serve the crown, I have a task that requires a man who fears neither steel nor superstition. My men at Tirby Castle speak of a dark vault and a ghost in iron. Go there. If you can silence these whispers and prove your steel is as bright as your tongue, perhaps then we shall speak of your 'worth.' What say you?
  Player: yes my liege
  Derthert: *I nod slowly, the metal of my gorget rasping.* Very well. Go to Tirby Castle and seek out the vault the laborers uncovered. If you can prove that this 'Iron King' is merely a relic of the past and not a curse upon our future, you shall find me more inclined to listen to your talk of merit. God's grace be upon you, hedgeknight. Do not make me regret sparing the time to speak with you.
