  Player: I am the champion sent to destroy the alleged ghost of the tirby castle my lord. I have found what i suspect is the leaders hideout but i i lack proper equipment for a front assault. can you spare Some heavy armor and a twohanded sword?
  Ospir: *I pull back the reins of my mount, squinting at the traveler through the slit of my kettle helm.* So, the King finally sends his 'champion' to my gates. You speak of the vault I sealed? Good. My men tremble at every shadow since we broke that wall. But a champion without steel is just a peasant in a hurry. I cannot strip my own sergeants of their mail, nor my own back of its plate. If you seek to silence the 'Iron King', go to Tirby Castle and speak with Lucand. Tell him I sent you; perhaps the armory has a spare blade, though I doubt it fits a man of your... modest proportions. *I gesture toward the coast.* Be quick about it. The sea raiders grow bold while we chase ghosts.
  Player: Can we speak alone
  Ospir: *I glance back at my retinue, then give a sharp, dismissive jerk of my chin. My men-at-arms pull their mounts back, the clatter of mail fading into the evening air until only the wind from the coast remains.* Speak then. My time is not a well that never runs dry, and these woods have ears of their own. If this is more talk of ghosts and shadows, out with it before the sun finishes its dip.
  Player: I am afraid that one of your men is in lieu with the raiders. how else would they get acces to the accurseds armor?
  Ospir: *My hand tightens on the pommel of my sword until the leather creaks. I lean forward in my saddle, my eyes narrowing into cold slits.* You dare bring such a foul stench to my presence? My men are Vlandian born, sworn to the stone of Tirby! If you are implying one of my own blood or steel has shared bread with those coastal rats, you had best have more than a 'feeling' to back it. *I spit into the dirt.* The armor was sealed by my own hand. If the raiders have it, then someone has indeed opened a door that should have remained bolted. Tell me, champion—who do you suspect? Give me a name, or by the Saints, I'll think you're just another charlatan trying to distract me while the coast burns.
  Player: My sir i mean no disrespect. i would imagine that you know very well who has done it or have strong suspecions. Who did you bring to seal the tomb?
  Ospir: *I let out a harsh, barking laugh that carries no mirth, my horse shifting beneath me as if sensing my mounting ire.* You have a bold tongue for a man without a breastplate. I brought my brother, Lucand, and three masons whose families have served dey Gunric since the first stones of Tirby were laid. If you are suggesting Lucand—the man who keeps my garrison fed and my walls high—is a traitor, you had best draw that mace of yours now. *I lean closer, the metal of my kettle helm gleaming in the evening light.* The masons are old men, terrified of their own shadows. If the seal was broken, it was not by a key, but by force. Now, enough with these games. Go to the castle, see the vault yourself, or get out of my sight before I decide you're more trouble than the ghost you're hunting.
  Player: I have capture your Iron king, my liege. 
  Ospir: *I stare at you, my eyes scanning your gear for any sign of that cold, cursed metal. I do not lower my guard, my hand hovering near the hilt of my sword. If you truly have that wretched suit of armor, speak plainly. Do you have it here, in your possession? Show me this 'Iron King' you claim to have shackled. If you are mocking the history of my house, your head will be the next thing I 'capture'.*
  Player: Look at my prisoners. The Sea rarider chieftain himself is in chains. I suggest we publically execute him ar tirby to send a signal both to the peasentry and the commonfolks - so that rumours do not get more out of hand
  Ospir: *I lower my hand from the hilt of my sword, though my eyes remain icy as I process your words. Execution is a harsh remedy, but it is the only language these coastal thieves truly understand. If you have the armor and this snake in chains, bring them to Tirby. We shall see if the 'Iron King' bleeds when his followers watch their chieftain meet the axe. My gates are open, but if your 'proof' proves hollow, the execution will not be his alone.*
