New dialogue with Oros (string_id: "lord_1_17", 26 messages):
  Player: Greeting my lord, do you brings news?
  Oros: Greetings, traveler. I carry the weight of my own business, mostly regarding the state of my holdings in Danustica and beyond. The winds of fate are quiet for now—the Empire knows no grand conflict at this hour. May I ask what draws you to this path in such late, clear evening?
  Player: I am a smith, i am simply gathering resources. do you have any need for my services?
  Oros: *I stroke my beard, observing the tools and callous on your hands with a keen, practiced eye.* You are a smith? That is a discipline I hold in high regard. There is a profound honesty in the forge that one rarely finds on the battlefield. *I pause, looking toward the horizon.* I have no immediate need for extra hands at Danustica, but one can never have enough quality steel or fine work. What is it you seek in exchange for your labor? And speak plainly—my time is as fleeting as the cooling of iron.
  Player: I will create any weapon to order. I am currently looking for caple bodyguard to keep me safe when travelling from city to city. But if you come to think of something you want created, i would happily do you a favour and do it for free.
  Oros: *I let out a short, dry chuckle as I adjust the weight of my mace on my belt.* A bodyguard, you say? By the grace of the Phoenix, I have nearly two hundred lances and archers under my banner currently patrolling this land. I believe my safety is well-guarded, traveler. However, your offer of a custom blade is not without merit. If you are truly a master of the forge, I may test your skills soon. For now, focus on your own safety; the roads are treacherous for a lone man with precious tools. Should our paths cross again near Danustica, perhaps we shall strike a bargain of steel.
  Player: I am soon travelling to Diathma, and need at least 2 bodyguards. Say if i can lend 2 of your stronger troops i will happily create you a legendary sword that will make envy the other lords.
  Oros: *I lean slightly into my saddle, the leather creaking under the weight of my armor, and narrow my eyes at you with a stern, unimpressed expression.* You speak with the confidence of a court poet, traveler. Asking for my veteran men—men who have bled for the Southern Empire and know the price of steel—in exchange for a blade I have yet to see? I am no fool. My troops serve the Empire, not the whims of passing strangers. If you wish to prove your worth as a smith, produce a quality blade, and perhaps we can discuss a proper commission. But do not ask me to compromise the discipline of my warband for a journey that offers me nothing. Travel safely to Diathma; I have no more time for these fables.
  Player: I meant no disrespect my liege. I will find you with a blade this realm could only dream of
  Oros: *I give a curt, measured nod, my expression softening only slightly.* Words are as light as steel shavings on an anvil, traveler. I shall hold you to that promise. If, upon your return, you bring a blade that truly reflects the artistry of our empire, we shall have much more to discuss regarding gold and patronage. Until then, keep your forge fires hot and your wits sharp. To the roads, then.
  Player: How much do you think a mastercrafted weapon in denars is worth, please humor me.
  Oros: *I fold my arms, my gaze lingering on the hilt of my sword before meeting your eyes once more.* A 'mastercrafted' label is thrown around by common peddlers at every market, traveler. But a true work of art? That is defined by the balance, the temper, and how the steel sings when it clears the scabbard. If you are speaking of a blade worthy of a high lord's table—something unique—the value is not merely in the iron. It could be thirty thousand denars, or it could be priceless. Do you think you can produce something truly that exceptional?
  Player: My liege, i have such a weapon. And i am willing to give it to you
  Oros: *I lower my arms and take a slow, deliberate step toward you, my expression sharpening with genuine curiosity.* A bold claim to make in the halls of Danustica. If you hold a blade that can stand under my inspection, let us see it. Place it upon the table. By the grace of the Phoenix, if its temper is as true and its balance as refined as you suggest, then you have my full attention—and perhaps, my patronage. Do not keep me in suspense; show me your work.
  Player: Here take this mastercrafteds 2 handed mace i have. Consider this marveloues piece of art a gift.
  Oros: *I move to the table, my calloused fingers reaching out to take the mace with a professional, almost reverent touch. I test the balance, feeling the heft and weight distribution—the mark of a true smith. I look up at you, my stern face softening into an expression of genuine, rare wonder.* By the gods, you were not exaggerating. The temper on this steel is superb. I have forged many things, yet this… this is a testament to your craft. I accept this gift with deep gratitude, traveler. You have proven your words were not merely wind. Tell me, what is your name? A craftsman of your caliber deserves to be known in Danustica.
  Player: they call me Osarios the Smith
  Oros: *I blink, a slight shadow of surprise crossing my features, before a warm, genuine smile breaks through my usual stern demeanor.* Osarios? A distinguished name—my own youngest son bears it. It seems destiny has a sense of humor, connecting a lord of the Empire with an artisan of such talent. Well then, Osarios the Smith, you are welcome here in Danustica. You have shown me true quality, and for that, you have a friend in the Mestricaros clan. What is it that you truly seek in your travels now that you have brought such a masterpiece to my hall?
  Player: I simply wish for security on my travels - i am no warrior, and i wish to travel to the nords to learn how they smith axes, and the the vlandians to create a lance that will make calradia fear you
  Oros: *I stroke my beard thoughtfully, the weight of the mace still resting in my hand.* A path to the northern and western lands is long and dangerous, Osarios. You seek the secrets of axes and lances to bring glory to my clan—a noble pursuit. While my legionaries remain bound to the defense of Danustica, I cannot deny that a smith of your caliber deserves protection. I shall provide you with a signed parchment, a seal of the Mestricaros. Display this, and my patrols will grant you safe passage throughout the region. And should you forge this masterpiece lance for my kin, know that you shall always have an open door and a full purse awaiting you here. Take this, and go with the Empire's blessing.
  Player: I wish not of money, dear patron. I wish for a retinue to protect me. I hope not a more suiteable Patron would provide me with 20 elite troops before you to safeguard me on my travels - as loyalty is not paid in silver.
  Oros: *I tighten my grip on the hilt of the mace you gave me, my expression sharpening as I look at you squarely.* You speak of loyalty as if it were a common coin to be traded for a mercenary's guard. These men are the shield of Danustica; they hold the line against our enemies, not for gold, but for the safety of our halls. I cannot strip my walls of their strength for your personal travels. If you truly crave the status and protection of the Mestricaros, then bind yourself to us officially. Join my clan, bear our colors, and you shall have the protection of our banners—not as a guest, but as kin. Choose, Osarios: do you seek a servant's escort, or do you seek the honor of the Mestricaros?
  Player: I accept this proposal. if you procvide me with a party. I will happily bear your colors and i will make weapon that no clan can compete with. 
  Oros: *I set the mace down carefully on the table and stand, looking you in the eyes, my expression solemn yet welcoming.* You have chosen well, Osarios. From this hour, you are no longer a traveling artisan, but a member of the Mestricaros. You shall bear our colors, and in return, you shall have the backing of our steel. I will grant you a small retinue to see you safely to your destinations. Forge well, and may the Empire honor your work.
  Player: about that small regiment. Can you put them in my party now?
  Oros: *I signal to a nearby sergeant, pointing toward a detachment of soldiers standing in the courtyard. Their armor clatters as they fall into formation.* These men are battle-hardened; they know the worth of the steel you forge and the necessity of the mission you bear. They are yours to command now. See that you lead them with the same precision you put into your work. Make no mistake, Osarios—their lives are now linked to your success. Go forth, forge that lance in the West, and return with glory that shall echo through all of Calradia.
