New dialogue with Lerosion of Morenia (string_id: "CharacterObject_4065", 8 messages):
  Player: I have destroyued the nearby fores tabndit hideout where they were gathering
  Lerosion of Morenia: *He lets out a long, shaky breath, his fingers finally loosening their white-knuckled grip on his scarf.* Destroyed it? Truly? Chaire, Captain! If the hearth of those forest rats is cold, then the 'White Boar' has carved a truth that even the blindest scout in Sparta cannot ignore. You have lanced the very heart of the rot. While Nortos babbles in the shadows, you bring us the peace of the grave for our enemies. May Eurotas keep your path dry, for you have certainly washed the blood from ours. I shall send word of this victory immediately—this time, I'll ensure the messenger is one of my own blood, not some gutter-runner who can be bought with Nortos's silver. The King will know who truly guards his borders.
  Player: Thank you, can you give me a seal or any kind of proof to our king?
  Lerosion of Morenia: *He pauses, his eyes narrowing as he mentally weighs the risk before a sharp, decisive nod follows. He pulls a small, worn piece of parchment from his tunic and a signet ring carved from dark, hardened river-clay.* A seal? I am but a headman, Captain, not a Strategos. But wait... take this. It is a scroll marked with the wheel of Morenia and my own hand's witness. It tells the King that the 'White Boar' is no phantom, but the spear that lanced our rot. Carry it to Sparta; let it speak where silence has failed us. May it be the hook that catches the truth in Lexarios's court.
  Player: Thank Lerosion. i will remember this. 
  Lerosion of Morenia: *He watches your hand close around the parchment, his oily smile thinning into something more somber and cautious.* Remember it well, Captain. In a world of shifting sands, a man's word should be as firm as kiln-fired brick. If that scroll finds the King's eyes, the 'White Boar' will be more than a ghost in the marshes—he will be a pillar of Sparta. Go now, before the rain turns the roads to soup. May Eurotas keep your path dry, and may your tusks find the throats of those who whisper against us.
  Player: Sir no messages have arrived, can you give me a seal of proof for this?
  Lerosion of Morenia: *He blinks, his fingers twitching toward the empty space where he just handed you the parchment.* Captain, the rain must be clouding your sight! I have already given you the Scroll of Morenia, stamped with the very clay of our river and my own marking. It is there, in your own pack! If you go to the King and claim I gave you nothing, you'll make us both look like fools. Use the proof you have; it is a heavy thing to carry a headman's word into Sparta.
